<DocsLayout title="Implementation" description="Create the backlog, set up operational tooling, and build SurfCoast Events with feature flags and monitoring from the start.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Implementation</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">You know the loop. The new dimension: operational tooling is part of the infrastructure, not an afterthought. Prometheus, Unleash, and PagerDuty are set up before feature work begins. You instrument as you build, not after.</p>

  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">Work through these in order:</p>

  <div class="grid gap-4">
    <Card title="1. Creating the backlog" subtitle="Generate and order the tickets — infrastructure and operational tooling first" href="/web-dev/projects/8/implementation/creating-the-backlog" />
    <Card title="2. Setup" subtitle="Project folder, Unleash, Prometheus, Grafana, PagerDuty, k6" href="/web-dev/projects/8/implementation/setup" />
    <Card title="3. Building" subtitle="The build loop with feature flags and trunk-based development" href="/web-dev/projects/8/implementation/building" />
  </div>

  <Callout variant="warning">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>This project has more tooling setup than any previous project.</strong> Budget time accordingly. Unleash (or LaunchDarkly), Prometheus, Grafana, PagerDuty, and k6 all need to be configured before feature work begins. The build order is: infrastructure, then feature flags, then application, then monitoring instrumentation, then load testing, then incident runbooks. Each layer builds on the previous.</p>
  </Callout>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Key ordering note:</strong> Operational infrastructure goes first. Before any feature work: Prometheus metrics endpoint, Unleash server, Grafana datasource, PagerDuty integration. Then core features (event listings, ticket sales, check-in). Then feature-flagged features. Then the event-day dashboard. Then load testing. You can't measure what you haven't instrumented.</p>
  </Callout>
</DocsLayout>
